Interview Questions
1. What is the super keyword in Java?
-->👉 Definition: super is a reference variable in Java that is used to refer to the immediate parent class object.
    ✅ Main uses:
    Access parent class variables
    Call parent class methods
    Call parent class constructor


2. How is super used to refer to immediate parent class object?
-->class Parent {
        int x = 10;
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        int x = 20;
    
        void show() {
            System.out.println(super.x); // refers to Parent's x
        }
    }


3. How can super be used to call parent class methods?
-->class Parent {
      void show() {
          System.out.println("Parent method");
      }
  }
  
  class Child extends Parent {
      void show() {
          super.show(); // calling parent method
          System.out.println("Child method");
      }
  }


4. How can super be used to access parent class variables when hidden by subclass?
-->class Parent {
        int value = 100;
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        int value = 200;
    
        void display() {
            System.out.println(value);       // child
            System.out.println(super.value); // parent
        }
    }


5. How is super() used to call parent class constructors?
-->class Parent {
        Parent() {
            System.out.println("Parent constructor");
        }
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        Child() {
            super(); // calls parent constructor
            System.out.println("Child constructor");
        }
    }



6. Can super() and this() be used together in a constructor? Why or why not?
-->❌ No

    👉 Reason: Both must be the first statement in constructor
        Only one can be first
    Child() {
        // super();
        // this(); ❌ not allowed together
    }


7. Can super be used in a static context? Why or why not?
-->❌ No
    
    👉 Reason:
    
    super refers to an object (parent instance)
    Static methods belong to class, not object
    static void test() {
        // super.show(); ❌ ERROR
    }




8. Difference between super and this in terms of constructor chaining.
-->super vs this (constructor chaining)
| Feature   | `this()`                               | `super()`               |
| --------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Refers to | Same class                             | Parent class            |
| Purpose   | Call another constructor in same class | Call parent constructor |
| Position  | First line only                        | First line only         |



9. How does super help in method overriding to call parent class version of method?
-->class Parent {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent version");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    void show() {
        super.show(); // calling parent version
        System.out.println("Child version");
    }
}


